practitioners to learn; but clinical studies demonstrate that students who regularly spend time in nature have reduced stress and anxiety levels and improved mood and outlook.In addition to the latest research, the authors present a step-by-step formula for constructing, sustaining, and evaluating Nature Rx programs, and they profile four such programs at American colleges. The practical guidance in Nature Rx alongside the authors' vigorous argument for the benefits of these programs for both students and institutions places Rakow and Eells at the forefront of this burgeoning movement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aCollege studentsxMental healthzUnited States. 0aNaturexPsychological aspects. 0aNature, Healing power of. 0aOutdoor recreationxPsychological aspects. 4aConsumer Health & Fitness. 4aEducation & History Of Education. 4aGeneral Science. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh  acollege students.  adealing with stress.  amental health.  anature prescription programs.1 aEells, Gregory T., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065198008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics, Law & Social Sciences 2019 ENGz978311061013008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2019z9783110606485oZDB-23-DSW40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501715303zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501715303423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501715303.jpg  a978-3